25 this Chapter or Chapter 14 of the General Statutes, the alcohol law enforcement agent or local
26 ABC officer shall send notice by electronic means or certified mail to the holder of the permit
27 within five business days of the issuance of the citation. Notice to Permit Holders. – If the
28 Commission receives a report from a law enforcement agency other than the Division of Alcohol
29 Law Enforcement of the Department of Public Safety or a local ABC officer documenting
30 violations of this Chapter or Chapter 14 of the General Statutes for conduct occurring on the
31 premises of a permitted establishment, the Commission shall send notice of the alleged violation
32 to the holder of the permit within five business days of receipt of the law enforcement agency
33 report. The written notice shall identify the currently alleged violations and the involved
34 employee. Nothing in this subsection shall prevent or limit the Commission from taking any
35 additional action warranted by the circumstances of the violation."
36
37 PART VI. REVIEW OF PERSONNEL RECORDS
38 SECTION 6.(a) Article 1 of Chapter 17C of the General Statutes is amended by
39 adding a new section to read:
40 "§ 17C-10.2. Transfer of certified law enforcement officers.
41 (a) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, a North Carolina law enforcement
42 agency considering an applicant for employment as a sworn law enforcement officer shall request
43 access to and review the complete personnel file of the applicant maintained by or on behalf of
44 any North Carolina law enforcement agency where the applicant was employed for any part of
45 the five-year period preceding the current application.
46 (b) With a release signed by the applicant, any North Carolina law enforcement agency
47 or any entity maintaining records of a law enforcement agency that previously employed the
48 applicant shall grant access to and may, if requested, provide a copy of the applicant's complete
49 personnel file, including confidential information as defined by G.S. 153A-98, 160A-168, and
50 126-24 to the law enforcement agency considering the applicant for employment.
Senate Bill 710-Second Edition Page 19

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (c) To the extent that confidential information as defined by G.S. 153A-98, 160A-168,
2 or 126-24 is maintained in the personnel file of any law enforcement agency or entity maintaining
3 records of a law enforcement agency that previously employed the applicant, that information
4 shall remain confidential in the files of any law enforcement agency obtaining the information
5 pursuant to this section.
6 (d) A law enforcement agency, any entity maintaining records of a law enforcement
7 agency, and the personnel of such agency or entity providing or receiving access to or copies of
8 an applicant's personnel file pursuant to subsections (a) and (b) of this section shall not be held
9 civilly or criminally liable for doing so."
10 SECTION 6.(b) Article 2 of Chapter 17E of the General Statutes is amended by
11 adding a new section to read:
12 "§ 17E-7.1. Transfer of certified law enforcement officers.
13 (a) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, a sheriff considering an applicant for
14 employment as a deputy sheriff shall request access to and review the complete personnel file of
15 the applicant maintained by or on behalf of any North Carolina law enforcement agency where
16 the applicant was employed for any part of the five-year period preceding the current application.
17 (b) With a release signed by the applicant, any North Carolina law enforcement agency
18 or any entity maintaining records of a law enforcement agency that previously employed the
19 applicant shall grant access to and may, if requested, provide a copy of the applicant's complete
20 personnel file, including confidential information as defined by G.S. 153A-98, 160A-168, and
21 126-24 to the sheriff's office considering the applicant for employment.
22 (c) To the extent that confidential information as defined by G.S. 153A-98, 160A-168,
23 or 126-24 is maintained in the personnel file of any law enforcement agency or entity maintaining
24 records of a law enforcement agency that previously employed the applicant, that information
25 shall remain confidential in the files of any sheriff's office obtaining the information pursuant to
26 this section.
27 (d) A law enforcement agency, any entity maintaining records of a law enforcement
28 agency, and the personnel of such law enforcement agency or entity providing or receiving access
29 to or copies of an applicant's personnel file pursuant to subsections (a) and (b) of this section
30 shall not be held civilly or criminally liable for doing so."
31
32 PART VII. REINSTATE G.S. 102-1.1
33 SECTION 7. Section 2(a) of S.L. 2023-92 is repealed.
34
35 PART VIII. MILITARY JUDGES OF THE NCNG APPOINTMENT MODIFICATIONS
36 SECTION 8.(a) G.S. 127A-50 reads as rewritten:
37 "§ 127A-50. Summary courts-martial.
38 (a) In the North Carolina National Guard, not in the service of the United States, summary
39 courts-martial may be appointed by any of the following:
40 (1) Any person who may convene a general or special court-martial.
41 (2) The commander of a battalion, comparable or higher command of the North
42 Carolina Army National Guard, provided that the commander is an officer of
43 the grade of major or above.
44 (3) The commander of a detached squadron, comparable or higher command of
45 the North Carolina Air National Guard, provided that the commander is an
46 officer of the grade of major or above.
47 (b) The court acting under this section shall consist of one officer who shall have the
48 power to administer oaths and try enlisted personnel of each respective command for breaches
49 of discipline and violations of laws governing those organizations. These courts shall also have
50 the power to impose punishments in like manner and to the extent prescribed by the Uniform
51 Code of Military Justice and Manual for Courts-Martial, United States, as shall be in use by the
Page 20 Senate Bill 710-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Armed Forces of the United States at the time of the offense, except that noofficer, the state
2 military judge, and a judge advocate detailed to the court as a hearing officer. A summary
3 court-martial shall have the authority to impose fines of not more than five hundred dollars
4 ($500.00), to impose forfeitures of two-thirds pay for one month, to restrict to limits, to impose
5 extra duty, and to reduce the rank of enlisted persons E7 and above by up to two ranks and
6 enlisted persons E6 and below to the rank of E1.
7 (c) No court acting under this section shall have the authority to impose confinement as
8 part of a sentence.
9 (d) There shall be no right during summary courts-martial to demand trial by
10 court-martial."
11 SECTION 8.(b) G.S. 127A-50.1 reads as rewritten:
12 "§ 127A-50.1. Military judges.
13 The Adjutant General shall appoint military judges to preside over courts-martial of the North
14 Carolina National Guard not in federal service. Minimum requirements for appointment as a
15 military judge are:are the following:
16 (1) Certification as a military judge by the Judge Advocate General of the United
17 States Army, Air Force, Navy, Marines, or Coast Guard.
18 (2) Designation as a judge advocate by the Judge Advocate General of the United
19 States Army, Navy, Air Force, Marines, or Coast Guard.
20 (3) Membership in the North Carolina National Guard, the National Guard of
21 another state, or the active or reserve components of the Armed Forces of the
22 United States.
23 (4) A member in good standing for at least 10 years of either of the following:
24 a. The bar of the highest court of this or any other state.
25 b. The bar of a federal court.
26 (5) Hold the rank of lieutenant colonel or above."
27 SECTION 8.(c) Section 8(a) of this Part is effective when it becomes law and applies
28 to summary courts-martial initiated on or after that date. Section 8(b) of this Part is effective
29 when it becomes law and applies to military judges serving on or after that date, except the
30 requirements of G.S. 127A-50.1, as amended by Section 8(b) of this Part, shall only apply to
31 appointments made on or after that date. The remainder of this Part is effective when it becomes
32 law.
33
34 PART IX. EFFECTIVE DATE
35 SECTION 9. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
36 law.
